Heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Wash (but do not peel) the @potato{2} and cut into 2cm chunks. Toss the potato chunks in @olive oil{1%tbsp}, @salt{1/4%tsp} and a few good grinds of @pepper{}. Lay out on a #baking tray{} and cook in the oven for ~{20-25%minutes} until crispy.

Cut open the @red pepper{1} and remove the core and any seeds. Cut into bite sized chunks. Toss in @olive oil{1/2%tbsp}, @salt{1/4%tsp} and a few good grinds of @pepper{}. Add these to the potatoes for the last ~{10%minutes} of their cooking.

Boil a large #pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Cut the @carrot{1}(cut in half lengthways) in half lengthways and cook in the boiling water for ~{6%minutes}. Add the @sugar snap peas{1} for the last ~{2%minutes} of cooking, then drain.

> Tip: You want your veg to be still 'al dente', meaning they still have a nice bite!

When you have drained the vegetables add them into a pan and stir in the @pesto{2}. Remove the green tops from the @radish{1/3} and cut them in half through the root. Cut each half in half again and add to the pan.

> Tip: Play around with presentation of the radishes, try cutting some into thin slices.

Toast off the @pine nuts{2} in a pan over a medium heat.

> Tip: Watch your nuts like a hawk as they can burn really quickly.

Mix the mini roasted potatoes and pepper with the pesto vegetables and @salt{1/4%tsp} and @pepper{1/4%tsp}. Use the baking tray you used for the roasties to reduce washing up!

> Tip: For those extra presentation points, try splitting some of the sugar snap peas down the middle.

Tear the @mozzarella{1} into bits and pick a handful of @basil{2}(leaves) from the stalks. Lay the spring vegetables on your plates and dot over the mozzarella and basil leaves. Finally sprinkle over the pine nuts.